  "prompt": "What is the starting package for EE at IITB?",
  "response": "The starting package for Electrical Engineering (EE) graduates at IIT Bombay (IITB) can vary significantly year to year, and depends heavily on factors such as:\n\n*   **Economic climate:** General job market conditions play a crucial role.\n*   **Company:** Different companies offer different salaries.\n*   **Job Role:** Core EE roles (hardware, embedded systems, power) might have slightly different starting packages compared to software/data science roles.\n*   **Individual Performance and Skills:** Academic record, projects, internships, and interview performance influence the offer.\n*   **Domestic vs. International Offers:** International offers typically have higher packages.\n\n**General Trends and Estimates (Based on past years):**\n\n*   **Domestic Packages:**\n    *   **Average:** While it fluctuates, the average domestic package for EE at IITB typically falls in the range of **\u20b920 LPA to \u20b935 LPA**. Keep in mind that averages can be skewed by a few very high offers.\n    *   **Median:** The median is often a more representative figure, and it is commonly in the range of **\u20b920 LPA to \u20b930 LPA**.\n    *   **Lowest:** Some students might get offers in the **\u20b912 LPA to \u20b918 LPA** range, especially for certain core EE jobs or smaller companies.\n    *   **Highest:** The highest domestic packages can be very high, potentially going above **\u20b980 LPA** or even more, but these are usually exceptions.\n*   **International Packages:** International offers are usually significantly higher, often in the range of **\u20b950 LPA to \u20b91 Crore+**, depending on the country, company, and role. It is important to consider the cost of living and taxes in those countries.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Official Data:** The most accurate information comes from the official placement reports released by IIT Bombay each year. These reports are typically available on the IITB placement website. You should look for the most recent placement report available.\n*   **CTC vs. Take-Home Pay:** Remember that the \"package\" (CTC - Cost to Company) includes various components like base salary, bonuses, stock options, benefits, and allowances. The actual take-home pay will be less due to taxes and other deductions.\n*   **Trends:** In recent years, there has been a trend of more EE graduates opting for jobs in software, data science, and finance, leading to a wider range of salary packages.\n\n**How to Find the Most Up-to-Date Information:**\n\n1.  **IIT Bombay Placement Website:** Search for the official placement reports for the Electrical Engineering department.\n2.  **Contact IITB Alumni:** Reach out to recent EE graduates from IITB on LinkedIn or other platforms and ask about their experiences and salary trends (be polite and respectful).\n\n**Disclaimer:** This information is based on general trends and past data. Actual starting packages can vary. Always refer to official sources for the most accurate information.\n",
